    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 4th with a clear target in **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, whose elite 82.12 score makes him the undeniable cornerstone of today\u2019s lineup. Facing a favorable matchup against Petty (6.57 xERA) with wind blowing out, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** benefits from a massive 19% boost in SP skill adjustment and a 14% platoon edge, making him the highest-upside play in the outfield. Following closely is **Junior Caminero** (65.79) and **Trea Turner** (65.20), both of whom offer elite production profiles; **Trea Turner** leverages his leadoff spot to capitalize on the weak matchup against Junk, while **Junior Caminero** remains a locked-in core piece despite the modest hurdle of facing Lauer. The team is also banking on **Yordan Alvarez**, whose elite 0.427 xwOBA keeps his efficiency high (63.86) even against the tougher profile of Yamamoto.\n\nIn terms of personnel movement, **Dillon Dingler** (56.64) holds the starting C1 spot, primarily fueled by a strong dynamic platoon advantage against the southpaw Tolle. The bench decision-making process was relatively straightforward due to the injury status of **Christian Yelich** and **Lars Nootbaar**, as well as the assignment of **Zac Veen** to the minors. Among the active reserves, **Caleb Durbin** remains on the outside looking in, unable to crack the starting nine due to his lack of a confirmed path to playing time today. While we are confident in the current configuration, managers should monitor the weather for **Carson Benge**; despite a strong score of 63.27 buoyed by a significant park factor, the 34% rain risk could jeopardize his output. **Hyeseong Kim** and **Colt Keith** remain our lowest-scoring starters; both are facing unfavorable platoon conditions against lefties, but provide necessary volume as we navigate the scarcity of our middle infield options.",
